The influence of reward on facial mimicry: no evidence for a significant effect of oxytocin.

Statistical analyses

Irene Trilla, Hanna Drimalla, Malek Bajbouj, Isabel Dziobek

Blinding integrity

At the end of the experimental session, participants indicated which treatment they thought they had received (oxytocin or placebo). Overall, 37% of the participants guessed correctly, 40% made an incorrect guess, and 23% reported to not know. A chi-square test indicated that the proportion of participants who made correct, incorrect and I dont know responses did not significantly differ between treatment groups.


# recode responses
d.quest$guess[(d.quest$treatment=='Oxytocin' & d.quest$treatment_guess=='oxt')| (d.quest$treatment=='Placebo' & d.quest$treatment_guess=='plc')] <- 'Correct'
d.quest$guess[(d.quest$treatment=='Oxytocin' & d.quest$treatment_guess=='plc')| (d.quest$treatment=='Placebo' & d.quest$treatment_guess=='oxt')] <- 'Incorrect'
d.quest$guess[d.quest$treatment_guess=='idk'] <- "I don't know"

To check whether treatment had an effect on the participants mood, we ran an ANOVA with Time (Pre, Post) as within-subject factor, and Treatment (Oxytocin, Placebo) as between-subject factor, for Positive affect and Negative affect separately.

Negative affect

Participants reported significantly less negative affect after treatment administration than at baseline. This effect was not significantly dependent on treatment group.

Reward manipulation

An associative learning paradigm was used to pair neutral faces with different reward values. On each trial, participants had to choose between one of two faces presented side by side. Two different face pairs appeared througout the task. For each pair, one face was associated with 60% probability of winning money (high reward condition), and the other face with 30% probability of winning money (low reward condition).

The task consisted of a minimum of three 10-trial blocks per face pair. Participants completed up to 4 additional 10-trial blocks per face pair if the proportion of high reward choices for that particular stimuli did not reach 80% by the end of the last block completed.

To test whether participants learned the reward associations, the proportion of high reward choices for each of the first 3 trial blocks were entered as the dependent variable in a 2 x 2 mixed ANOVA with Block (First, Second, Third) as within-subject factor, and Treatment (Oxytocin, Placebo) as between-subject factor. The Holm-Bonferroni method was applied to adjust for multiple comparisons in post-hoc tests.


# anova
m.cond <- afex::aov_4(prophirew ~ block*treatment + (block|id), d.rew)
kable(nice(m.cond), caption='ANOVA on the proportion of high reward choices by learning block:') %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c('hover', 'condensed', 'responsive'))
ANOVA on the proportion of high reward choices by learning block:
Effect df MSE F ges p.value
treatment 1, 58 0.10 0.26 .004 .61
block 1.99, 115.52 0.01 36.51 *** .10 <.0001
treatment:block 1.99, 115.52 0.01 0.16 .0005 .85

In line with the expected reward learning, there was a significant effect of Block. Post-hoc tests showed that participants chose the high reward faces more often in the second and third blocks, as compared to the first block. The difference between the second and third blocks did not reach statistical significance. There was no significant main effect of Treatment, nor a significant interaction Block*Treatment.


# post-hoc tests
m.cond.emmeans <- emmeans(m.cond, c('block'))
m.cond.posthoc <- summary(update(pairs(m.cond.emmeans), by=NULL, adjust='holm'))

# effect sizes for post-hoc tests
d_pair1 <- effsize::cohen.d(d.rew$prophirew[d.rew$block=='Block 1'],d.rew$prophirew[d.rew$block=='Block 2'])
d_pair2 <- effsize::cohen.d(d.rew$prophirew[d.rew$block=='Block 1'],d.rew$prophirew[d.rew$block=='Block 3'])
d_pair3 <- effsize::cohen.d(d.rew$prophirew[d.rew$block=='Block 2'],d.rew$prophirew[d.rew$block=='Block 3'])
m.cond.posthoc$cohen.d <- c(d_pair1$estimate, d_pair2$estimate, d_pair3$estimate)

# table post-hoc results

There was a change in the perceived pleasantness of the faces after the reward learning task, indicated by a significant interaction Reward*Time. As shown in the follow-up tests, while there were no significant differences in pleasantness ratings at baseline, faces associated with high reward were rated as more pleasant than faces associated with low reward after the reward learning task. Treatment did not significantly interact with these effects, nor had an overall influence on pleasantness ratings.


# tailored contrasts for post-hoc tests

Facial mimicry (EMG)

Analysis sample

Due to technical problems, EMG data of two participants were not collected. Data from two additional participants were excluded from the EMG analyses, as they responded incorrectly in more than 20% of the attention control questions of the mimicry task.

The EMG analysis sample thus included 29 participants in the oxytocin group and 27 participants in the placebo group.

Statistical plan

EMG data was analyzed using linear mixed models (LMM). Separate LMMs were ran to test EMG responses to observation of happy and angry facial expressions. Mimicry of happiness was defined as stronger response of ZM vs.CS when watching happy facial expressions. Mimicry of anger was defined as stronger CS vs.ZM when watching angry facial expressions.


Mimicry of no-reward faces

First, we ran two LMMs to examine the direct influence of oxytocin on facial mimicry of happiness (model 1) and of anger (model 2). Only data from trials in which participants viewed no-reward faces (i.e.novel faces that did not appear in the reward learning task) were fitted in these LMMs.

  • Model 1:

    [EMG scores for happy, no-reward faces] ~ Muscle + Treatment + Muscle*Treatment + (1|Participant) + (1|Stimuli)

  • Model 2:

    [EMG scores for angry, no-reward faces] ~ Muscle + Treatment + Muscle*Treatment + (1|Participant)


Mimicry of low & high reward faces

Second, we ran two LMMs to examine the influence of reward, and the modulatory effects of oxytocin, on facial mimicry of happiness (model 3) and of anger (model 4). Only data from trials in which participants viewed faces successfully associated with low reward and high reward values in the reward learning task were fitted in these LMMs.

  • Model 3 :

    [EMG scores for happy, reward faces] ~ Muscle + Reward + Treatment + Muscle*Reward + Muscle*Treatment + Reward*Treatment + Muscle*Reward*Treatment + (1|Participant) + (1|Stimuli)

  • Model 4:

    [EMG scores for angry, reward faces] ~ Muscle + Reward + Treatment + Muscle*Reward + Muscle*Treatment + Reward*Treatment + Muscle*Reward*Treatment + (1|Participant) + (1|Stimuli)

By-participant and by-stimulus random intercepts were included in the LMMs to account for non-independencies in the data. Note, though, that the random intercept for stimulus was removed from Model 2 as otherwise it led to singular fit.

Sum-to-zero contrasts were used for all predictors. P-values for fixed effects were computed based on Satterthwaite approximation for denominator degrees of freedom.


# set contrasts for LMM
options(contrasts=rep('contr.sum', 2))

  • id is the participant identifier. Note: each participant completed 96 trials, but the data frame contains two rows per trial (1 for each muscle recorded), which sums up to 112 rows per ID.
  • treatment indicates whether participant took intranasal oxytocin or placebo.
  • emotion indicates whether the participant observed a video of a happy or an angry facial expression during that trial.
  • reward indicates whether the face observed in the video was previously associated with low reward or high reward values, or if it was a novel face that was not presented during the reward learning task (no reward).
  • learnt indicates whether the association between the face presented in that trial and the corresponding reward value had been successfully assimilated (TRUE) or not (FALSE) in the reward learning task (see Reward manipulation for the learning criterion applied).
  • muscle refers to whether the EMG data corresponds to the corrugator supercilii (CS) or the zygomaticus major (ZM).
  • emg are Z-standardized, baseline-corrected EMG scores averaged over the interval from 1500 to 4000 ms post-stimulus onset.
  • stimulus identifies the actor that appeared in the video observed during that trial.

Mimicry of no-reward faces


Mimicry of happiness (model 1)

Only the time-window between 1500 and 4000 ms post-stimulus onset (grey shade) was used for statistical analysis. Error bars represent within-subject 95% confidence intervals.

Model 1 revealed a main effect of Muscle, which confirms the occurance of facial mimicry of happiness: observation of happy facial expressions elicited higher ZM compared to CS activity. Contrary to our expectations, the interaction Muscle*Treatment was not significant, providing no evidence for a direct effect of oxytocin on mimicry of happiness.

# MODEL 1: EMG responses to unconditioned happy faces

# select data
d.emg.hap <- subset(d.emg, emotion=='Happy' & reward=='No reward')

# RANDOM-effects structure: the maximal random-effects structure led to singular fit.
# By-participant and by-stimulus random slopes of muscle were dropped from the models.

# lmm
mh <- lmerTest::lmer(emg ~ muscle*treatment + (1|id) + (1|stimulus), data=d.emg.hap)
summary(mh, corr=F)

## Formula: emg ~ muscle * treatment + (1 | id) + (1 | stimulus)
##    Data: d.emg.hap
## 
## REML criterion at convergence: 3814.5

Equivalence testing

Because null-hypothesis significance testing can only reject the presence of an effect, we cannot conclude that oxytocin does not influence facial mimicry based on the non-significant results reported above. Using the Two One-Sided Tests (TOST) procedure of equivalence testing (Lakens, 2017), we reexamined our main null findings to test whether the effect of oxytocin on facial mimicry was statistically equivalent to the placebo effect, or whether our data was just not sensitive enough to detect the predicted group differences. We limited this analysis to EMG responses to happy faces, as our task failed to elicit mimicry of anger.

Given that there is no clear theoretical boundary for oxytocins social-cognitive effects for setting the equivalence bounds (Quintana, 2018), we defined the smallest effect size of interest based on the smallest effect size detectable with 80% power given our sample size (Quintana, 2018; Tabak et al., 2019). The alpha level was set to 0.05.

Effect of oxytocin on mimicry of happiness

First, we applied the TOST procedure to test the null effect of oxytocin on EMG responses to happy expressions of unconditioned faces. Given that the TOST procedure is based on t-tests, we reduced the original interaction Muscle*Treatment tested in the LMM by computing mimicry indices (i.e.difference score between CS and ZM activity in response to happy faces) for each participant. Positive scores indicate the occurrence of mimicry of happiness.


# Compute average EMG responses
d.tost <- d.emg[d.emg$reward=='No reward',] %>%
  dplyr::group_by(id, treatment, emotion, muscle, reward) %>%
  dplyr::summarise(emg=mean(emg))

d.tost$muscle <- factor(d.tost$muscle, levels=c('ZM', 'CS'), labels=c('zm', 'cs'))
d.tost$emotion <- factor(d.tost$emotion, levels=c('Happy', 'Angry'), labels=c('hap', 'ang'))
d.tost$reward <- factor(d.tost$reward, levels=c('No reward'), labels=c('norew'))
d.tost$varname<- with(d.tost, paste(muscle, emotion, reward, sep='_'))
d.tost<- d.tost[,c('id', 'treatment', 'varname', 'emg')]
d.tost <- tidyr::spread(data=d.tost, key=varname, value=emg)

# Compute mimicry indices (ZM minus CS)
d.tost$mim_hap_norew <- d.tost$zm_hap_norew-d.tost$cs_hap_norew
d.tost$mim_ang_norew <- d.tost$zm_ang_norew-d.tost$cs_ang_norew

# Define the SESOI based on the smallest detectable effect size
smallest_es <- pwr::pwr.t2n.test(power=0.8, n1=sum(d.tost$treatment=='Placebo'), n2=sum(d.tost$treatment=='Oxytocin'), alternative='two.sided', sig.level=0.05)
seosi <- smallest_es$d

# TOST procedure: mimicry of HAPPINESS (oxt vs. plc)
tost_norew <- TOSTER::TOSTtwo(m1=mean(d.tost$mim_hap_norew[d.tost$treatment=='Placebo']),
                              m2=mean(d.tost$mim_hap_norew[d.tost$treatment=='Oxytocin']),
                              sd1=sd(d.tost$mim_hap_norew[d.tost$treatment=='Placebo']),
                              sd2=sd(d.tost$mim_hap_norew[d.tost$treatment=='Oxytocin']),
                              n1=sum(d.tost$treatment=='Placebo'), n2=sum(d.tost$treatment=='Oxytocin'),
                              low_eqbound_d=-seosi, high_eqbound_d=seosi,
                              var.equal=FALSE, alpha=0.05)

Effect of oxytocin on the reward modulation of mimicry of happiness

Second, we tested the oxytocin effects on the influence of reward on facial mimicry. To reduce the original LMM three-way interaction Muscle*Reward*Treatment, we subtracted the mimicry index of high reward faces from the mimicry index of low reward faces for each participant. Positive scores indicate stronger mimicry of happiness in response to high reward vs.low reward faces.


# Compute average EMG responses, excl. unlearnt trials
d.tost.rew <- d.emg[d.emg$reward!='No reward' & d.emg$learnt==TRUE,] %>%
  dplyr::group_by(id, treatment, emotion, muscle, reward) %>%
  dplyr::summarise(emg=mean(emg))

d.tost.rew$muscle <- factor(d.tost.rew$muscle, levels=c('ZM', 'CS'), labels=c('zm', 'cs'))
d.tost.rew$emotion <- factor(d.tost.rew$emotion, levels=c('Happy', 'Angry'), labels=c('hap', 'ang'))
d.tost.rew$reward <- factor(d.tost.rew$reward, levels=c('Low reward', 'High reward'), labels=c('lorew', 'hirew'))
d.tost.rew$varname<- with(d.tost.rew, paste(muscle, emotion, reward, sep='_'))
d.tost.rew<- d.tost.rew[,c('id', 'treatment', 'varname', 'emg')]
d.tost.rew <- tidyr::spread(data=d.tost.rew, key=varname, value=emg)

# Compute mimicry indices and difference score for reward condition (High reward - Low reward)
d.tost.rew$mim_hap_lorew <- d.tost.rew$zm_hap_lorew-d.tost.rew$cs_hap_lorew
d.tost.rew$mim_ang_lorew <- d.tost.rew$zm_ang_lorew-d.tost.rew$cs_ang_lorew
d.tost.rew$mim_hap_hirew <- d.tost.rew$zm_hap_hirew-d.tost.rew$cs_hap_hirew
d.tost.rew$mim_ang_hirew <- d.tost.rew$zm_ang_hirew-d.tost.rew$cs_ang_hirew
d.tost.rew$mim_hap_rewdiff <- d.tost.rew$mim_hap_hirew-d.tost.rew$mim_hap_lorew
d.tost.rew$mim_ang_rewdiff <- d.tost.rew$mim_ang_hirew-d.tost.rew$mim_ang_lorew

# Define the SESOI based on the smallest detectable effect size
smallest_es_rew <- pwr::pwr.t2n.test(power=0.8, n1=sum(d.tost.rew$treatment=='Placebo'), n2=sum(d.tost.rew$treatment=='Oxytocin'), alternative='two.sided', sig.level=0.05)
seosi_rew <- smallest_es_rew$d

# TOST procedure: mimicry of HAPPINESS (oxt vs. plc)
tost_rew <- TOSTER::TOSTtwo(m1=mean(d.tost.rew$mim_hap_rewdiff[d.tost.rew$treatment=='Placebo']),
                            m2=mean(d.tost.rew$mim_hap_rewdiff[d.tost.rew$treatment=='Oxytocin']),
                            sd1=sd(d.tost.rew$mim_hap_rewdiff[d.tost.rew$treatment=='Placebo']),
                            sd2=sd(d.tost.rew$mim_hap_rewdiff[d.tost.rew$treatment=='Oxytocin']),
                            n1=sum(d.tost.rew$treatment=='Placebo'), n2=sum(d.tost.rew$treatment=='Oxytocin'),
                            low_eqbound_d=-seosi_rew, high_eqbound_d=seosi_rew,
                            var.equal=FALSE, alpha=0.05)

## t-value lower bound: 3.95    p-value lower bound: 0.0001

## low eqbound: -0.8018

## The null hypothesis test was non-significant, t(48.98) = 1.085, p = 0.283, given an alpha of 0.05.
## Based on the equivalence test and the null-hypothesis test combined, we can conclude that the observed effect is statistically not different from zero and statistically equivalent to zero.
